1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,960
 Waiting for something to happen that you're expecting to happen but that doesn't happen

2
00:00:06,960 --> 00:00:10,240
 is really awkward, isn't it?

3
00:00:10,240 --> 00:00:12,760
 You guys just feel really awkward?

4
00:00:12,760 --> 00:00:15,640
 Trust me, I looked around the room, you guys were looking pretty awkward.

5
00:00:15,640 --> 00:00:17,200
 None of you were like looking at me in the eyes.

6
00:00:17,200 --> 00:00:18,200
 It's like, "Oh, no, no, no.

7
00:00:18,200 --> 00:00:19,200
 What's Andrew doing?

8
00:00:19,200 --> 00:00:20,200
 He's doing something weird.

9
00:00:20,200 --> 00:00:21,200
 Don't look at him."

10
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:28,800
 Waiting for something to happen that we're expecting to happen but that doesn't happen

11
00:00:28,800 --> 00:00:31,400
 is one of the strangest experiences for us as human beings.

12
00:00:31,400 --> 00:00:33,840
 It's one of the hardest things for us to grapple with.

13
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:38,840
 I understand this deeply well because my daughter and I just this past week experienced this

14
00:00:38,840 --> 00:00:41,720
 at the extreme level.

15
00:00:41,720 --> 00:00:45,080
 We've just been in Queenstown on a family holiday in the last week.

16
00:00:45,080 --> 00:00:50,280
 And about a month ago before we left, my daughter Mia, she goes, "When we get to Queenstown,

17
00:00:50,280 --> 00:00:53,120
 dad, I want you and I to do the canyon swing."

18
00:00:53,120 --> 00:00:58,200
 Now, on paper, the canyon swing sounded like a pretty easy thing.

19
00:00:58,200 --> 00:01:01,480
 That sounds like not a big deal, the canyon swing.

20
00:01:01,480 --> 00:01:05,040
 She then sent me videos of people doing this canyon swing.

21
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:09,240
 And I quickly realized that this is one of the New Zealand ways of trying to kill you.

22
00:01:09,240 --> 00:01:12,560
 Like bungee jumping was invented in New Zealand, right?

23
00:01:12,560 --> 00:01:16,760
 Canyon swing is like a bungee jumping experience but with a swing.

24
00:01:16,760 --> 00:01:23,460
 Basically, what it is is you go up to this very high platform over this very deep canyon.

25
00:01:23,460 --> 00:01:26,080
 You then get placed in a harness.

26
00:01:26,080 --> 00:01:28,520
 You then get dropped off the platform.

27
00:01:28,520 --> 00:01:35,360
 You have a 100-meter free fall drop into this canyon where you hope that the mechanism catches

28
00:01:35,360 --> 00:01:40,000
 you at the bottom of that drop and then swings you out for miles out into this canyon.

29
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,840
 You do this huge swing.

30
00:01:41,840 --> 00:01:47,120
 My daughter was like, "This would be the greatest bonding experience with my dad ever."

31
00:01:47,120 --> 00:01:52,520
 I was like, "This is the worst thing I have heard, but I love my daughter more than I

32
00:01:52,520 --> 00:01:53,720
 care for my sanity."

33
00:01:53,720 --> 00:01:58,320
 So, we signed up for the canyon swing.

34
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:01,000
 We got up there that day.

35
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:05,400
 My mindset on the day was this, "Don't look at any videos.

36
00:02:05,400 --> 00:02:07,760
 Don't look at anybody doing it.

37
00:02:07,760 --> 00:02:09,860
 Ignorance is bliss.

38
00:02:09,860 --> 00:02:11,880
 Just get up there and do it."

39
00:02:11,880 --> 00:02:17,360
 And there was like 10 of us in the van that were all paid to do this canyon swing experience.

40
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:18,960
 My daughter was so sweaty.

41
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:19,960
 Her hands were sweaty.

42
00:02:19,960 --> 00:02:21,320
 My heart rate was going crazy.

43
00:02:21,320 --> 00:02:23,800
 We get up there, they put all the harnesses in us and stuff.

44
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:27,720
 And I recognize there's 10 other people in the queue to do this, but I recognize if I

45
00:02:27,720 --> 00:02:30,360
 have to wait, are you with me?

46
00:02:30,360 --> 00:02:34,680
 If I have to wait to be the 10th person to do this, I am not going to do this, right?

47
00:02:34,680 --> 00:02:38,160
 Like the only way this is going to happen is that me and I go first.

48
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:41,040
 So, I was rude.

49
00:02:41,040 --> 00:02:42,960
 In that 20 minutes, I was not a pastor.

50
00:02:42,960 --> 00:02:44,480
 I just want you to know.

51
00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:46,840
 I was just a normal person, okay?

52
00:02:46,840 --> 00:02:47,940
 And a rude one at that.

53
00:02:47,940 --> 00:02:52,200
 We pushed our way forward through everybody so that we would go first.

54
00:02:52,200 --> 00:02:58,360
 They then said, "Okay, how do you want to be dropped?"

55
00:02:58,360 --> 00:03:00,540
 Because New Zealand is not just enough to try to kill you.

56
00:03:00,540 --> 00:03:03,000
 You get to decide how you're going to be killed.

57
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:05,200
 So they're like, "How do you want to be dropped?

58
00:03:05,200 --> 00:03:06,880
 Here's a plethora of ways."

59
00:03:06,880 --> 00:03:11,640
 And they showed us this screen with 15 different ways that you could choose to be dropped.

60
00:03:11,640 --> 00:03:12,880
 My daughter's looking at the screen.

61
00:03:12,880 --> 00:03:16,280
 I'm thinking, "Lord Jesus."

62
00:03:16,280 --> 00:03:21,600
 She decides that the best way to get dropped is by the chainsaw.

63
00:03:21,600 --> 00:03:23,480
 So the chainsaw works like this.

64
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:25,480
 You get into the harness thing.

65
00:03:25,480 --> 00:03:32,960
 They then suspend you on a crane out so that you're hanging but not dropping over the valley.

66
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:39,920
 And then one of the people in the team takes a chainsaw and cuts the rope, and that's how

67
00:03:39,920 --> 00:03:42,680
 you fall.

68
00:03:42,680 --> 00:03:46,600
 So my daughter decides that the chainsaw is the best way to do the canyon swing.

69
00:03:46,600 --> 00:03:48,660
 So sure enough, we sit in the harnesses.

70
00:03:48,660 --> 00:03:53,320
 They take us on this little crane out so that we're dangling free over the thing, but we

71
00:03:53,320 --> 00:03:55,000
 haven't dropped yet.

72
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,600
 This was the worst seconds of my life.

73
00:03:59,600 --> 00:04:04,660
 Because you know it's going to happen, but you don't know when it's going to happen.

74
00:04:04,660 --> 00:04:09,640
 You're waiting for something to happen that isn't happening, that you know should happen

75
00:04:09,640 --> 00:04:11,900
 and could happen at any moment.

76
00:04:11,900 --> 00:04:16,320
 And to make matters worse, they get this chainsaw and they go, "Ha ha ha ha ha ha," like this.

77
00:04:16,320 --> 00:04:19,880
 And they do this like five or six times.

78
00:04:19,880 --> 00:04:21,880
 And each time you're like, "Oh, God, it didn't happen.

79
00:04:21,880 --> 00:04:22,880
 Oh, it didn't happen.

80
00:04:22,880 --> 00:04:23,880
 Oh, it didn't happen.

81
00:04:23,880 --> 00:04:24,880
 Ah!"

82
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:29,920
 Because one time they finally do it, and they cut through the rope with the chainsaw, and

83
00:04:29,920 --> 00:04:32,880
 you hurtle into this canyon, 100-meter freefall drop.

84
00:04:32,880 --> 00:04:37,040
 Oh my gosh, it was the worst experience of my life.

85
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:40,640
 But my daughter loved it.

86
00:04:40,640 --> 00:04:43,880
 And the whole way down in the freefall, you can go to my Instagram, by the way, later

87
00:04:43,880 --> 00:04:45,960
 and see the video of the whole thing.

88
00:04:45,960 --> 00:04:51,240
 But the whole way down in the freefall, my daughter buried herself into my chest.

89
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:54,280
 And I thought, "Isn't that a beautiful picture of the father?

90
00:04:54,280 --> 00:05:01,120
 Isn't that a beautiful picture of like, 'I'm Jesus and there's my daughter,' buried into

91
00:05:01,120 --> 00:05:07,480
 my chest as we're plummeting down this canyon, waiting for something to happen that hasn't

92
00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:10,200
 happened, but that we expected to happen?"

93
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:14,880
 It's one of the scariest, most awkward, hardest experiences that we have as human beings.

94
00:05:14,880 --> 00:05:19,160
 I don't know if you've thought about this, but we don't like to wait.

95
00:05:19,160 --> 00:05:20,160
 Amen?

96
00:05:20,160 --> 00:05:21,440
 Like, we just don't.

97
00:05:21,440 --> 00:05:22,440
 We don't like to wait.

98
00:05:22,440 --> 00:05:26,760
 And it's because I think we've been conditioned in the world right now, in this high-tech,

99
00:05:26,760 --> 00:05:31,420
 consumeristic, driven world, that waiting is a bad thing.

100
00:05:31,420 --> 00:05:35,800
 That if something is of value, is something that is good, then you should receive it straight

101
00:05:35,800 --> 00:05:36,800
 away.

102
00:05:36,800 --> 00:05:41,900
 That in fact, the quicker it comes, the more value we generally place upon it.

103
00:05:41,900 --> 00:05:46,840
 So when you make your Taobao order, you want it to come in a couple of days, not a week.

104
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:48,880
 And if it comes in a couple of days, what do you say?

105
00:05:48,880 --> 00:05:51,120
 "Wow, Taobao's really good.

106
00:05:51,120 --> 00:05:52,520
 It came in like two days.

107
00:05:52,520 --> 00:05:53,960
 I couldn't believe it."

108
00:05:53,960 --> 00:05:57,480
 When you order a coffee, you don't want to have to wait for your coffee.

109
00:05:57,480 --> 00:05:59,960
 You want your coffee to come as quickly as possible.

110
00:05:59,960 --> 00:06:04,620
 We think that when something happens quickly, then it's good.

111
00:06:04,620 --> 00:06:07,440
 When it happens slowly, it's bad.

112
00:06:07,440 --> 00:06:12,100
 I will prove this to you now by showing you the scariest experience that all of us have

113
00:06:12,100 --> 00:06:13,600
 on a regular basis.

114
00:06:13,600 --> 00:06:15,600
 It's this one.

115
00:06:15,600 --> 00:06:18,240
 Yeah.

116
00:06:18,240 --> 00:06:21,740
 That one is one of the scariest experiences any of us ever have now.

117
00:06:21,740 --> 00:06:26,480
 It's when your phone is like doing the whole, you know, wheel of death spin thing, and the

118
00:06:26,480 --> 00:06:30,920
 website's not loading, you know, the social media thing's not coming, whatever it is,

119
00:06:30,920 --> 00:06:33,040
 and we get this, what do we want to do?

120
00:06:33,040 --> 00:06:34,040
 We want an upgrade.

121
00:06:34,040 --> 00:06:36,920
 "Give me a better phone, faster connection.

122
00:06:36,920 --> 00:06:41,920
 I need 5G plus, plus, plus, because 5G no longer is good enough for me."

123
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:47,840
 When we are thrown into a place where that sort of thing takes place, we think something's

124
00:06:47,840 --> 00:06:49,840
 broken.

125
00:06:49,840 --> 00:06:52,260
 We think this isn't working.

126
00:06:52,260 --> 00:06:53,440
 We need an upgrade.

127
00:06:53,440 --> 00:06:58,280
 We need to change something because this thing right here is not working for me anymore.

128
00:06:58,280 --> 00:07:03,840
 The old saying, "Good things come to those who wait," has been replaced with, "Good things

129
00:07:03,840 --> 00:07:07,360
 come to those who are first in line."

130
00:07:07,360 --> 00:07:11,320
 Those who push everybody out the way and go into the canyon first.

131
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:16,960
 Good things go to those who act quicker than anyone else.

132
00:07:16,960 --> 00:07:22,960
 Intelligence used to be defined by how much you could retain in your memory.

133
00:07:22,960 --> 00:07:27,320
 Now intelligence is primarily defined in our digital age by how quickly you can access

134
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:30,600
 information.

135
00:07:30,600 --> 00:07:38,600
 We think waiting is weakness, which is a big challenge to us Christians.

136
00:07:38,600 --> 00:07:43,280
 It's a big challenge because we have, in our Christianity, in our modern church, taken

137
00:07:43,280 --> 00:07:49,880
 this worldview into our spirituality, into our faith, into the ways that we think about

138
00:07:49,880 --> 00:07:54,600
 church, into even, I would say, our doctrine.

139
00:07:54,600 --> 00:08:00,080
 Now we think that God needs to act and He has to act immediately.

140
00:08:00,080 --> 00:08:06,120
 If God doesn't act immediately, then there's something wrong with God.

141
00:08:06,120 --> 00:08:08,560
 Because if God was all loving and all kind and all merciful and He knew what I wanted

142
00:08:08,560 --> 00:08:12,840
 and He knew my prayers and I prayed regularly every day, surely He should bless me.

143
00:08:12,840 --> 00:08:13,840
 Surely He should pour out.

144
00:08:13,840 --> 00:08:14,840
 Surely He should act.

145
00:08:14,840 --> 00:08:16,180
 He should respond quickly.

146
00:08:16,180 --> 00:08:20,880
 We think that God, if He was all loving, if He really was real, if He really was true,

147
00:08:20,880 --> 00:08:25,220
 if He was as the Bible described Him to be, when He thinks, when He does, He acts quickly.

148
00:08:25,220 --> 00:08:26,740
 He acts immediately.

149
00:08:26,740 --> 00:08:32,820
 So when God doesn't seem to act immediately in our lives, we, as Christians, very quickly

150
00:08:32,820 --> 00:08:38,300
 begin to question His character, question His nature, and sometimes, if it's prolonged

151
00:08:38,300 --> 00:08:44,180
 over a long period of time, maybe even question His existence.

152
00:08:44,180 --> 00:08:48,980
 Because surely if God's good, then I should receive quickly.

153
00:08:48,980 --> 00:08:54,220
 I should receive in the time that I want, in the time frame that I've decided, "Oh,

154
00:08:54,220 --> 00:08:58,040
 I've been praying, but He's not come through," which is really interesting.

155
00:08:58,040 --> 00:08:59,500
 Because here's what happens next.

156
00:08:59,500 --> 00:09:04,620
 Not only when Christians need to wait do we begin to blame God, because we have a wrong

157
00:09:04,620 --> 00:09:09,900
 theology of Him, we also then begin to blame ourselves.

158
00:09:09,900 --> 00:09:14,740
 Have you ever been in a situation in a church or in a small group where maybe the people

159
00:09:14,740 --> 00:09:17,500
 around you know that you've been waiting a long time for something, and they're like,

160
00:09:17,500 --> 00:09:19,820
 "Man, you've been waiting a long time.

161
00:09:19,820 --> 00:09:20,820
 Have you checked your spirit?

162
00:09:20,820 --> 00:09:23,820
 Have you checked your heart?

163
00:09:23,820 --> 00:09:27,500
 There might be some unconfessed sin in your life because you're still waiting for that

164
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:28,580
 promise.

165
00:09:28,580 --> 00:09:30,900
 You're still waiting for your healing.

166
00:09:30,900 --> 00:09:31,900
 Did you pray properly?

167
00:09:31,900 --> 00:09:34,220
 When was the last time you went to church?

168
00:09:34,220 --> 00:09:36,100
 Have you been a good person?"

169
00:09:36,100 --> 00:09:40,100
 Because if you were all those things, then surely you would receive straight away.

170
00:09:40,100 --> 00:09:43,740
 Surely God would give immediately, because surely that's who God is.

171
00:09:43,740 --> 00:09:47,580
 So when God doesn't give, we either blame God or we, funnily enough, blame each other

172
00:09:47,580 --> 00:09:50,020
 or blame ourselves.

173
00:09:50,020 --> 00:09:54,700
 Maybe the reason why God is not blessing me, not answering my prayer is because I haven't

174
00:09:54,700 --> 00:09:57,440
 tithed recently.

175
00:09:57,440 --> 00:10:00,940
 Or maybe it's because I haven't confessed my sin recently.

176
00:10:00,940 --> 00:10:06,060
 And we come up with all these ideas because we have this thinking that if God is in it,

177
00:10:06,060 --> 00:10:10,780
 it will happen straight away.

178
00:10:10,780 --> 00:10:15,500
 I know I've wrestled with God this way in the waiting periods of my life.

179
00:10:15,500 --> 00:10:18,780
 There have been many periods in my life where I've had to wait considerably on something

180
00:10:18,780 --> 00:10:19,940
 from the Lord.

181
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:23,180
 You guys, if you've been a part of the Vine for a while, will know my infertility journey.

182
00:10:23,180 --> 00:10:30,260
 My wife and I, for eight years, from a diagnosis of male infertility, so on my side, we then

183
00:10:30,260 --> 00:10:31,260
 had to wait.

184
00:10:31,260 --> 00:10:33,860
 We had to wait for tests and procedures.

185
00:10:33,860 --> 00:10:35,660
 We had to wait for donor insemination.

186
00:10:35,660 --> 00:10:38,460
 We then had to wait for an adoption process.

187
00:10:38,460 --> 00:10:40,120
 The whole thing took about eight years.

188
00:10:40,120 --> 00:10:43,940
 And trust me, that was a painful waiting process.

189
00:10:43,940 --> 00:10:48,580
 And I'm honest with you that in that waiting process, I doubted God.

190
00:10:48,580 --> 00:10:50,820
 I attacked His character.

191
00:10:50,820 --> 00:10:55,840
 I thought He was angry or distant or just not nice.

192
00:10:55,840 --> 00:10:59,540
 And then when I got through that, I began to attack myself, that obviously there was

193
00:10:59,540 --> 00:11:03,520
 something wrong with me, that I had done something wrong or whatever, whatever it might be.

194
00:11:03,520 --> 00:11:05,620
 It's fascinating, isn't it?

195
00:11:05,620 --> 00:11:11,260
 So we take something that the world has defined, if it comes quickly, it's of higher value.

196
00:11:11,260 --> 00:11:16,260
 And we've applied that to our faith, which has caused us to either blame God or blame

197
00:11:16,260 --> 00:11:17,260
 ourselves.

198
00:11:17,260 --> 00:11:22,520
 And God stands back from all of that and He's like, "Have you read the Bible?"

199
00:11:22,520 --> 00:11:28,660
 Because pretty much every hero of faith in Scripture, guess what?

200
00:11:28,660 --> 00:11:31,420
 Had a waiting time, a waiting period.

201
00:11:31,420 --> 00:11:36,340
 And sure, there are those moments where God does the miraculous in the immediacy.

202
00:11:36,340 --> 00:11:39,340
 Moses' staff in the water sees part.

203
00:11:39,340 --> 00:11:41,660
 Jesus' feeding of the 5,000.

204
00:11:41,660 --> 00:11:45,540
 You can go through Scripture, yes, and find these amazing moments where God acts immediately

205
00:11:45,540 --> 00:11:47,260
 on the faith of some people.

206
00:11:47,260 --> 00:11:53,900
 That happens, of course, but you'll find more stories where God in His sovereignty and in

207
00:11:53,900 --> 00:12:03,580
 His grace and in His love says something, but it doesn't happen for a period of time.

208
00:12:03,580 --> 00:12:09,140
 And I know in my own journey that I don't like to wait.

209
00:12:09,140 --> 00:12:11,180
 How about you?

210
00:12:11,180 --> 00:12:14,580
 Maybe for some of you in this room, maybe there's seasons of waiting that you're in

211
00:12:14,580 --> 00:12:16,020
 right now.

212
00:12:16,020 --> 00:12:21,020
 I think, for example, in our community of our asylum seekers and refugees, and I think

213
00:12:21,020 --> 00:12:22,460
 of you.

214
00:12:22,460 --> 00:12:28,140
 And I think for you, many of you have waited 10 plus years for the UNHCR to make a decision

215
00:12:28,140 --> 00:12:32,420
 on your case or for the Hong Kong government to make a decision on your case, and you're

216
00:12:32,420 --> 00:12:34,820
 still waiting.

217
00:12:34,820 --> 00:12:39,340
 I think of our domestic helpers here in our community, many of whom have to wait long

218
00:12:39,340 --> 00:12:44,100
 periods of time before they can return back to their families and visit their children,

219
00:12:44,100 --> 00:12:47,580
 their husband, visit their family.

220
00:12:47,580 --> 00:12:53,100
 I think of people in our community that are currently waiting on a diagnosis, waiting

221
00:12:53,100 --> 00:12:57,900
 on a healing, waiting on a promise from God to come through.

222
00:12:57,900 --> 00:13:03,820
 I think of those that are waiting on a spouse, have long held a desire to meet a life partner

223
00:13:03,820 --> 00:13:05,500
 and are still waiting.

224
00:13:05,500 --> 00:13:11,060
 I think of those that are waiting on an email, waiting on a job application or a new job,

225
00:13:11,060 --> 00:13:17,340
 those that are waiting on someone to say sorry, those that are waiting to be able to say sorry.

226
00:13:17,340 --> 00:13:22,940
 I think all of us in this room probably understand seasons of waiting, and most of us in this

227
00:13:22,940 --> 00:13:26,860
 room would be currently in such a season.

228
00:13:26,860 --> 00:13:29,240
 And it was interesting because as we were praying as a leadership for how we wanted

229
00:13:29,240 --> 00:13:34,100
 to start 2026, normally I've been involved in this church for 30 years now almost, normally

230
00:13:34,100 --> 00:13:38,180
 here at the Vine, we start the year with a super positive, super woohoo, super rah-rah

231
00:13:38,180 --> 00:13:42,580
 kind of message and sermon series to start the year with much inspiration and hope.

232
00:13:42,580 --> 00:13:46,860
 And as we were praying for 2026, we felt like the Lord was saying, "In this season of uncharted,

233
00:13:46,860 --> 00:13:50,700
 so if you've been coming to the Vine, you'll know that over the last year, we've been speaking

234
00:13:50,700 --> 00:13:55,980
 about the fact that we're in an uncharted season as a church, uncharted, this idea that

235
00:13:55,980 --> 00:13:59,580
 we're like those early pioneers on the boats who kind of go out and they go beyond the

236
00:13:59,580 --> 00:14:04,620
 charts like no one's ever sailed that far and they're literally paving new ground.

237
00:14:04,620 --> 00:14:07,940
 And we felt like the Holy Spirit last year was saying that the Vine is in a season of

238
00:14:07,940 --> 00:14:08,940
 being uncharted.

239
00:14:08,940 --> 00:14:14,380
 Here's the reality, when you're in an uncharted season, which we believe still carries forward

240
00:14:14,380 --> 00:14:18,940
 into 2026, there are going to be moments and seasons of waiting.

241
00:14:18,940 --> 00:14:22,260
 There are going to be moments and seasons of waiting.

242
00:14:22,260 --> 00:14:25,500
 So as we were praying for this year and how do we start this year, we felt like the Lord

243
00:14:25,500 --> 00:14:31,340
 saying rather than starting on like a rah-rah inspiring 2026, it's going to be awesome.

244
00:14:31,340 --> 00:14:37,260
 We felt like the Lord said, "You've got to start pastorally because there are a lot of

245
00:14:37,260 --> 00:14:43,860
 people in the community who are waiting right now and the waiting is hard and the waiting

246
00:14:43,860 --> 00:14:50,100
 is challenging and I want to meet them in the waiting.

247
00:14:50,100 --> 00:14:54,120
 And so I want you to teach about what it is to wait on the Lord."

248
00:14:54,120 --> 00:14:57,380
 So if you're here and you are not in a season of waiting, you can come back in five weeks'

249
00:14:57,380 --> 00:15:00,500
 time.

250
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:01,500
 Don't do that.

251
00:15:01,500 --> 00:15:05,340
 Whether you're in a season of waiting or not, obviously there's going to be great truths

252
00:15:05,340 --> 00:15:10,540
 throughout these five weeks, but I have a sense in my heart that almost all of us are

253
00:15:10,540 --> 00:15:15,420
 in a season where the picture we had this morning as we were praying was we're carrying

254
00:15:15,420 --> 00:15:17,340
 bruised hearts a little.

255
00:15:17,340 --> 00:15:19,220
 The waiting has been tough.

256
00:15:19,220 --> 00:15:24,700
 The waiting has gone on for too long and it's hurt and there's some bruising in our hearts

257
00:15:24,700 --> 00:15:29,220
 and we just felt like the Holy Spirit saying, "Open up Scripture over the next five weeks

258
00:15:29,220 --> 00:15:35,300
 and teach around this idea of what it is to wait on the Lord."

259
00:15:35,300 --> 00:15:39,420
 And I do believe that as we do this, it's going to be a prophetic time for you.

260
00:15:39,420 --> 00:15:40,620
 This is what the fast is about.

261
00:15:40,620 --> 00:15:46,060
 So the devotions that Carla spoke about, and a lot of you came after that announcement,

262
00:15:46,060 --> 00:15:48,500
 so I'm just going to make it really quick again.

263
00:15:48,500 --> 00:15:50,180
 We're doing January devotions.

264
00:15:50,180 --> 00:15:51,900
 They're starting tomorrow.

265
00:15:51,900 --> 00:15:57,100
 You need to join a WhatsApp group because they're audio devotions.

266
00:15:57,100 --> 00:16:00,700
 You can scan the QR code in front of your chair later on to get that WhatsApp group

267
00:16:00,700 --> 00:16:02,140
 and sign up.

268
00:16:02,140 --> 00:16:05,860
 All the devotions are going to be on waiting.

269
00:16:05,860 --> 00:16:08,600
 All these five weeks are going to be on this idea of waiting.

270
00:16:08,600 --> 00:16:14,340
 And we're going to base it on a specific passage, Psalm 27.

271
00:16:14,340 --> 00:16:18,900
 And the reason why we're basing it on Psalm 27 is because Psalm 27 takes us on a bit of

272
00:16:18,900 --> 00:16:19,900
 a journey.

273
00:16:19,900 --> 00:16:26,900
 And interestingly, it's a journey that psychologists have outlined as the journey emotionally that

274
00:16:26,900 --> 00:16:30,260
 we often go on when it comes to waiting periods in our lives.

275
00:16:30,260 --> 00:16:36,260
 In fact, there are four predominant emotional states that we find in seasons of waiting.

276
00:16:36,260 --> 00:16:39,220
 The first is confusion.

277
00:16:39,220 --> 00:16:44,220
 So this idea that kind of like we're in this place of confusion, that we don't understand,

278
00:16:44,220 --> 00:16:45,800
 why is this happening to me?

279
00:16:45,800 --> 00:16:47,180
 Why am I in this place?

280
00:16:47,180 --> 00:16:50,280
 Why am I having to wait for an answer or wait for this, whatever it is?

281
00:16:50,280 --> 00:16:53,940
 So there's the initial stage of confusion.

282
00:16:53,940 --> 00:16:58,940
 Now usually after confusion, if confusion doesn't get the answers or we can't find the

283
00:16:58,940 --> 00:17:03,620
 answers to why this is happening, which is often the case in a season of waiting, we

284
00:17:03,620 --> 00:17:05,940
 then move into anxiety.

285
00:17:05,940 --> 00:17:07,920
 Am I always going to feel like this?

286
00:17:07,920 --> 00:17:10,260
 Is this the way it's always going to be?

287
00:17:10,260 --> 00:17:11,540
 Am I ever going to get out of this?

288
00:17:11,540 --> 00:17:13,300
 Am I ever going to get through this?

289
00:17:13,300 --> 00:17:14,700
 Is there ever going to be change?

290
00:17:14,700 --> 00:17:20,300
 We enter into this place of nervous anxiety, this anxiety within our spirit.

291
00:17:20,300 --> 00:17:24,740
 Now there are healthy ways of dealing with anxiety, but there are unhealthy ways and

292
00:17:24,740 --> 00:17:27,060
 often that's through suppression.

293
00:17:27,060 --> 00:17:31,700
 What happens in seasons of waiting is if we have this confusion, which enters into anxiety

294
00:17:31,700 --> 00:17:35,620
 and we don't deal with that anxiety in a good way, we suppress it, that will lead us into

295
00:17:35,620 --> 00:17:39,460
 the next one, which is hopelessness.

296
00:17:39,460 --> 00:17:44,380
 Hopelessness is sort of the idea of like, "Well, I guess this sort of stuff always happens

297
00:17:44,380 --> 00:17:45,380
 to me.

298
00:17:45,380 --> 00:17:48,580
 Well, I guess this will just be the way things are.

299
00:17:48,580 --> 00:17:51,340
 I guess I'm just going to have to live with this."

300
00:17:51,340 --> 00:17:55,900
 We fall into a place of hopeless thinking and hopelessness within our spirit, and when

301
00:17:55,900 --> 00:17:58,220
 that's not dealt with, that leads to a place of self-pity.

302
00:17:58,220 --> 00:18:00,700
 "Oh, this is me.

303
00:18:00,700 --> 00:18:01,700
 This is who I am.

304
00:18:01,700 --> 00:18:04,940
 Oh, I'm such a victim of a system or a victim of whatever."

305
00:18:04,940 --> 00:18:10,380
 We begin to think of ourselves as a victim of something far greater or grander, and we

306
00:18:10,380 --> 00:18:13,700
 slip into these four emotional states super easy.

307
00:18:13,700 --> 00:18:17,860
 Now it is kind of a linear thing, but it's very sickly as well.

308
00:18:17,860 --> 00:18:21,260
 Often when we get to that self-pity, we find ourselves confused again, which leads us back

309
00:18:21,260 --> 00:18:25,540
 into anxiety, which leads us to hopelessness, and the whole thing goes on.

310
00:18:25,540 --> 00:18:33,260
 And the question we should have is, "Is there another way of waiting?"

311
00:18:33,260 --> 00:18:37,660
 Because that way is not working for me.

312
00:18:37,660 --> 00:18:42,740
 And Psalm 27, which we're basing this series in over the next five weeks, I think offers

313
00:18:42,740 --> 00:18:46,660
 us another path, another way.

314
00:18:46,660 --> 00:18:48,140
 It's a psalm of great hope.

315
00:18:48,140 --> 00:18:54,020
 There are actually over 200 scriptures in the Bible on the topic of waiting, 200 of

316
00:18:54,020 --> 00:18:56,780
 them, which is an incredible amount.

317
00:18:56,780 --> 00:19:02,260
 And within those 200, I did a survey of it in preparation for this series, and I looked

318
00:19:02,260 --> 00:19:05,900
 at kind of what are those 200 are trying to talk about.

319
00:19:05,900 --> 00:19:12,020
 And here's the thing, the Bible predominantly speaks about seasons of waiting as a gift.

320
00:19:12,020 --> 00:19:18,580
 I don't know if you've thought about it that way before, but as a gift, that actually seasons

321
00:19:18,580 --> 00:19:21,060
 of waiting are a blessing to us.

322
00:19:21,060 --> 00:19:23,940
 Now I know if you're in a prolonged season of waiting right now, that's not going to

323
00:19:23,940 --> 00:19:26,860
 jive particularly well with you.

324
00:19:26,860 --> 00:19:31,700
 And it's not that the Bible doesn't address the confusion and the anxiety and the hopelessness.

325
00:19:31,700 --> 00:19:36,380
 There's a lot of encouraging passages within scripture of those who are in a hard waiting

326
00:19:36,380 --> 00:19:38,780
 season and God speaks encouragement.

327
00:19:38,780 --> 00:19:44,340
 But the predominant teaching in scripture on waiting is the idea that it is a gift.

328
00:19:44,340 --> 00:19:48,280
 That in seasons of waiting, you're forced to slow down.

329
00:19:48,280 --> 00:19:51,100
 You're forced to reevaluate some things.

330
00:19:51,100 --> 00:19:55,820
 You're forced to begin to think of God different to how you thought of Him before.

331
00:19:55,820 --> 00:20:02,220
 But there are some fresh and new ways of encountering Him within that season.

332
00:20:02,220 --> 00:20:07,380
 Seasons of waiting are a gift because in them we discover a part of the character of Jesus

333
00:20:07,380 --> 00:20:13,940
 that perhaps we've not had to see before, or perhaps we've not embraced before.

334
00:20:13,940 --> 00:20:17,860
 And seasons of waiting are also described in scripture as one of the primary ways that

335
00:20:17,860 --> 00:20:19,420
 God disciples His people.

336
00:20:19,420 --> 00:20:22,340
 I mean, think about it for a second.

337
00:20:22,340 --> 00:20:29,660
 The seasons of waiting are often a stripping season, a removing from myself of my own self-reliance,

338
00:20:29,660 --> 00:20:34,300
 a stripping away of the things that I rely on within myself so that I'm more open to

339
00:20:34,300 --> 00:20:36,460
 trusting and relying on God.

340
00:20:36,460 --> 00:20:42,740
 Seasons of waiting are a reminder to me that I am not God, that I don't have what He has

341
00:20:42,740 --> 00:20:49,640
 and that I must rely on Him, throw myself upon Him, open my heart to Him.

342
00:20:49,640 --> 00:20:52,220
 Seasons of waiting are a gift.

343
00:20:52,220 --> 00:20:55,060
 And Psalm 27 opens up for us what this gift looks like.

344
00:20:55,060 --> 00:20:56,940
 And I want to do something a little bit different this morning.

345
00:20:56,940 --> 00:20:58,460
 I want to read through the Psalm to you.

346
00:20:58,460 --> 00:21:01,940
 We normally put the scripture on the screen, but I'm actually going to read it to you without

347
00:21:01,940 --> 00:21:02,940
 it on the screen.

348
00:21:02,940 --> 00:21:07,340
 I want to invite you just to receive this Psalm afresh.

349
00:21:07,340 --> 00:21:10,060
 For some of you, it might be the first time that you've ever heard this Psalm.

350
00:21:10,060 --> 00:21:12,080
 For others, it's a familiar Psalm to you.

351
00:21:12,080 --> 00:21:15,580
 Whatever it might be, can I invite you just to close your eyes and maybe just open your

352
00:21:15,580 --> 00:21:17,540
 spirit, open your heart?

353
00:21:17,540 --> 00:21:24,780
 And I want you to listen to David's beautiful words from Psalm 27.

354
00:21:24,780 --> 00:21:27,300
 He says, "The Lord is my light and my salvation.

355
00:21:27,300 --> 00:21:29,020
 Whom should I fear?

356
00:21:29,020 --> 00:21:30,700
 The Lord is a stronghold to my life.

357
00:21:30,700 --> 00:21:33,340
 Of whom should I be afraid?

358
00:21:33,340 --> 00:21:37,660
 When evil people advance against me to devour my flesh, when my enemies and my foes attack

359
00:21:37,660 --> 00:21:40,900
 me, they will stumble and fall.

360
00:21:40,900 --> 00:21:44,620
 Though an army besiege me, my heart will not fear.

361
00:21:44,620 --> 00:21:50,540
 Though even war break out against me, even then I will be confident.

362
00:21:50,540 --> 00:21:53,900
 One thing I ask of the Lord, this is what I seek.

363
00:21:53,900 --> 00:21:58,220
 That I may dwell in the house of the Lord all the days of my life, to gaze upon the

364
00:21:58,220 --> 00:22:01,740
 beauty of the Lord and to seek Him in His temple.

365
00:22:01,740 --> 00:22:04,660
 For in the day of trouble, He will keep me safe in His dwelling.

366
00:22:04,660 --> 00:22:10,180
 He will hide me in the shelter of His tabernacle and set me high upon a rock.

367
00:22:10,180 --> 00:22:15,740
 And my head will be exalted above my enemies who surround me at His tabernacle.

368
00:22:15,740 --> 00:22:17,940
 Will I sacrifice with shouts of joy?

369
00:22:17,940 --> 00:22:21,900
 I will sing and make music to the Lord.

370
00:22:21,900 --> 00:22:24,860
 So hear my voice when I call, O Lord.

371
00:22:24,860 --> 00:22:27,860
 Be merciful to me and answer me.

372
00:22:27,860 --> 00:22:31,300
 For my heart says of you, seek His face.

373
00:22:31,300 --> 00:22:34,340
 Your face, Lord, I will seek.

374
00:22:34,340 --> 00:22:35,940
 Do not hide your face from me.

375
00:22:35,940 --> 00:22:38,300
 Do not turn your sermon away in anger.

376
00:22:38,300 --> 00:22:40,020
 You have been my helper.

377
00:22:40,020 --> 00:22:42,660
 Do not reject me or forsake me, O God, my Savior.

378
00:22:42,660 --> 00:22:46,740
 Though my father and my mother forsake me, the Lord will receive me.

379
00:22:46,740 --> 00:22:49,420
 So teach me your ways, O Lord.

380
00:22:49,420 --> 00:22:52,120
 Lead me in a straight path because of my oppressors.

381
00:22:52,120 --> 00:22:55,140
 Do not turn me over to the desires of my foes.

382
00:22:55,140 --> 00:23:00,060
 For false witnesses rise up against me, breathing out violence.

383
00:23:00,060 --> 00:23:07,340
 But I am still confident of this, that I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of

384
00:23:07,340 --> 00:23:08,340
 the living.

385
00:23:08,340 --> 00:23:10,660
 So wait for the Lord.

386
00:23:10,660 --> 00:23:15,580
 Be strong and take heart and wait for the Lord.

387
00:23:15,580 --> 00:23:21,660
 Father, I pray over the next five weeks that you would do something deep in this community.

388
00:23:21,660 --> 00:23:26,300
 Father, I pray you would pastor your church.

389
00:23:26,300 --> 00:23:31,180
 Lord, I pray that you would heal bruised hearts.

390
00:23:31,180 --> 00:23:36,420
 I pray that as we open up this incredible psalm, you would speak deeply to each one

391
00:23:36,420 --> 00:23:37,420
 of us.

392
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:41,180
 And we pray this in your name.

393
00:23:41,180 --> 00:23:42,180
 Amen.

394
00:23:42,180 --> 00:23:45,540
 The final part of the psalm, I mean, it is a brutal psalm of honesty.

395
00:23:45,540 --> 00:23:50,300
 This is one of those psalms that you go to and go like, "It's okay to be expressing my

396
00:23:50,300 --> 00:23:53,900
 heart to the Lord in pretty brutal ways," because David does say throughout the psalm.

397
00:23:53,900 --> 00:23:55,660
 But right at the end, he says, "I'm confident of this.

398
00:23:55,660 --> 00:23:57,660
 I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living."

399
00:23:57,660 --> 00:23:59,060
 We'll preach on that in a few weeks' time.

400
00:23:59,060 --> 00:24:01,540
 And then he says, "Wait for the Lord.

401
00:24:01,540 --> 00:24:03,660
 Be strong and take heart and wait for him."

402
00:24:03,660 --> 00:24:07,420
 The Hebrew word that David uses for wait here, which is used throughout the Old Testament,

403
00:24:07,420 --> 00:24:12,140
 is a very important one because it's very different to how we think about waiting in

404
00:24:12,140 --> 00:24:13,780
 our modern context.

405
00:24:13,780 --> 00:24:18,460
 The Hebrew word is k'fa, and k'fa is this idea.

406
00:24:18,460 --> 00:24:26,820
 It literally means this, to gather up or to bind together, to look and to see.

407
00:24:26,820 --> 00:24:33,620
 So to take some things and bind them up together, to gather stuff together, to then look and

408
00:24:33,620 --> 00:24:34,900
 to see.

409
00:24:34,900 --> 00:24:37,020
 The word itself is a verb word.

410
00:24:37,020 --> 00:24:42,980
 It's an action word, which is fascinating because this is the opposite to how we generally

411
00:24:42,980 --> 00:24:46,180
 think about waiting in the modern context.

412
00:24:46,180 --> 00:24:50,460
 You see, David's explaining that this is what it means to wait for the Lord.

413
00:24:50,460 --> 00:24:52,540
 It means to bind together.

414
00:24:52,540 --> 00:24:55,980
 It means to gather together, to look and to expect.

415
00:24:55,980 --> 00:25:01,100
 In other words, that I have these threads in the waiting season of a promise from God,

416
00:25:01,100 --> 00:25:05,100
 of a word that he may have spoken into my spirit, of a passage that meant something

417
00:25:05,100 --> 00:25:09,700
 to me, of a conversation I had with a pastor or a friend in my community group.

418
00:25:09,700 --> 00:25:12,860
 There are these things that are hope anchors for me.

419
00:25:12,860 --> 00:25:18,820
 To wait on the Lord is to gather up those things and in them find an expectation and

420
00:25:18,820 --> 00:25:25,340
 an excitement of leaning forward to see what the Lord is about to do.

421
00:25:25,340 --> 00:25:29,440
 Which should blow your mind because in our modern context, when we think about waiting,

422
00:25:29,440 --> 00:25:31,740
 we predominantly think about it as inactivity.

423
00:25:31,740 --> 00:25:35,980
 Oh, I'm in a season of waiting.

424
00:25:35,980 --> 00:25:38,660
 I'm just in a...

425
00:25:38,660 --> 00:25:41,180
 How you doing?

426
00:25:41,180 --> 00:25:42,780
 Pretty good.

427
00:25:42,780 --> 00:25:43,780
 Yeah.

428
00:25:43,780 --> 00:25:44,780
 I'm waiting.

429
00:25:44,780 --> 00:25:45,780
 Same.

430
00:25:45,780 --> 00:25:46,780
 Yeah.

431
00:25:46,780 --> 00:25:47,780
 Okay, good.

432
00:25:47,780 --> 00:25:50,060
 We'll just sit here and wait together.

433
00:25:50,060 --> 00:25:52,140
 Are you with me?

434
00:25:52,140 --> 00:25:53,140
 You don't look like you're waiting.

435
00:25:53,140 --> 00:25:54,140
 You don't look like you're waiting.

436
00:25:54,140 --> 00:25:55,140
 Yeah, yeah, yeah.

437
00:25:55,140 --> 00:25:56,140
 There you go.

438
00:25:56,140 --> 00:25:57,140
 Good man.

439
00:25:57,140 --> 00:25:58,140
 Good man.

440
00:25:58,140 --> 00:25:59,800
 You're not waiting anymore.

441
00:25:59,800 --> 00:26:01,820
 Waiting in our context is inactivity.

442
00:26:01,820 --> 00:26:02,820
 It's idleness.

443
00:26:02,820 --> 00:26:05,400
 But waiting in the Hebrew thinking is not inactivity.

444
00:26:05,400 --> 00:26:06,400
 It's not idleness.

445
00:26:06,400 --> 00:26:07,400
 It is...

446
00:26:07,400 --> 00:26:08,400
 Listen to this.

447
00:26:08,400 --> 00:26:11,080
 It is active anticipation of change.

448
00:26:11,080 --> 00:26:12,600
 Come on, church.

449
00:26:12,600 --> 00:26:16,680
 Waiting is an active anticipation of change.

450
00:26:16,680 --> 00:26:22,880
 It is not the reality of that change in the moment because then you're no longer waiting.

451
00:26:22,880 --> 00:26:26,500
 It is not the reality that the prayer has come through, that things have happened and

452
00:26:26,500 --> 00:26:27,840
 that God has acted.

453
00:26:27,840 --> 00:26:34,560
 It is the active anticipation that a time is coming where God is going to act, where

454
00:26:34,560 --> 00:26:37,960
 he will come through, when the promise will be delivered.

455
00:26:37,960 --> 00:26:40,800
 That's what it means in the Bible to wait on the Lord.

456
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:41,800
 It is to hold...

457
00:26:41,800 --> 00:26:43,160
 Let me put it this way.

458
00:26:43,160 --> 00:26:45,640
 Waiting is a prophetic act.

459
00:26:45,640 --> 00:26:46,640
 Come on, church.

460
00:26:46,640 --> 00:26:49,260
 I don't know if you ever thought about waiting that way.

461
00:26:49,260 --> 00:26:51,680
 Waiting is a prophetic act.

462
00:26:51,680 --> 00:26:58,520
 It is a standing on the ramparts, looking out and believing that the promise is coming.

463
00:26:58,520 --> 00:27:03,360
 Waiting in the Hebrew is not this kind of like, "Oh, gosh, whatever."

464
00:27:03,360 --> 00:27:04,360
 Waiting is like this.

465
00:27:04,360 --> 00:27:05,360
 Are you with me?

466
00:27:05,360 --> 00:27:08,440
 If you can't see me, I'll stand up.

467
00:27:08,440 --> 00:27:10,480
 But waiting is like this.

468
00:27:10,480 --> 00:27:16,280
 There's this beautiful picture in the New Testament of what waiting is like.

